Analysis:
While this bill is largely focused on physical infrastructure like roads, bridges, and transit, investment in rural infrastructure supports agricultural communities. According to Politico, the agriculture-related provisions include: 
○ $40 billion to states build out broadband internet infrastructure and $14 billion to help consumers afford their internet bills. The bill also includes $2 billion for the Agriculture Department, including the ReConnect Program, to expand broadband in rural areas
○ $3.5 billion for direct carbon removal projects to establish four regional hubs designed to capture carbon already in the atmosphere;
○ $3.3 billion to the Forest Service and Interior Department to fight wildfires including through controlled burns, mechanical thinning and firefighting resources;
○ $45 million per year for five years for the Forest Service to carry out burned area rehabilitation programs;
○ $300 million over five years to USDA for the Emergency Watershed Restoration Program, which helps local communities respond after natural disasters;
○ Provisions in the REPLANT Act, first introduced by Senate Ag Committee Debbie Stabenow (D-Mich.), which removes the $30 million cap on the Reforestation Trust Fund and aims to plant 1.2 billion trees in national forests over 10 years;
○ $127 billion for roads, bridges, ports and waterways, as well as tens of billions of dollars for other traditional infrastructure projects that are crucial to farmers and ag exporters;
○ Billions more in funding for water infrastructure for the West.

In addition to this bill, Democrats are working on the separate, broader $1.75 trillion Build Back Better package (H.R.5376) through the reconciliation process.

